  "prompt": "What it is like to be a Hindu in Pakistan?",
  "response": "Being a Hindu in Pakistan can be challenging due to several social, religious, and political factors:\n\n1. Religious Discrimination:\n- Hindus face systemic discrimination and are often treated as second-class citizens\n- Limited representation in government and public institutions\n- Social stigma and prejudice\n\n2. Religious Persecution:\n- Frequent incidents of harassment, violence, and forced conversions\n- Limited legal protection against religious persecution\n- Targeted attacks on Hindu temples and communities\n\n3. Socio-Economic Challenges:\n- Limited economic opportunities\n- Marginalization in many professional and social spheres\n- Concentrated in lower socio-economic strata, often in menial jobs\n\n4. Population Status:\n- Hindus are a small minority (approximately 2-3% of Pakistan's population)\n- Concentrated mainly in Sindh province, particularly in rural areas\n\n5. Cultural Identity:\n- Struggle to maintain cultural and religious practices\n- Pressure to assimilate into the dominant Muslim culture\n- Fear of expressing religious identity openly\n\n6. Legal Vulnerabilities:\n- Weak legal safeguards against discrimination\n- Challenges in property rights and personal status laws\n- Difficulty in seeking justice in case of communal tensions\n\nDespite these challenges, some Hindu communities in Pakistan continue to preserve their cultural and religious traditions.",
